[2] UK (Wale)
Date: Wed 11 Apr 2012
Source: South Wales Evening Post [edited]
http://www.thisissouthwales.co.uk/Outbreak-alert-kids-given-jab/story-15780307-detail/story.html

Outbreak alert
------------
An outbreak of measles could easily happen in South West Wales because of the number of children not being vaccinated with the MMR jab, a health chief has warned. Public Health Wales is currently investigating an outbreak of the disease at a North Wales school. Now director of public health at Abertawe Bro Morgannwg University Health Board, Dr Sara Hayes, has warned a similar outbreak could be seen in the area due to a shortfall in the number of children being vaccinated. Ms Hayes said: "All children need to receive two doses of the MMR vaccination, which protects against mumps and rubella as well as measles. "Until 95 per cent of children have received two doses of the vaccine, there is still a risk that measles outbreaks will happen.

"In the counties of Swansea, Bridgend and Neath Port Talbot (the areas covered by the health board), latest figures show that 14.6 per cent of 5-year-old children have had no doses of MMR or only one. "This means that more than 800 children in the area are not fullyvaccinated, and this is not enough to prevent outbreaks. "Although children should receive their first dose of MMR at 12 months of age and the second at 3 years and 4 months, it is never too late to catch up on missed doses. "To avoid an outbreak in the Abertawe Bro Morgannwg area, I am urging parents whose children are not fully vaccinated to speak to their GP as soon as possible." More than 40 cases of measles are currently being investigated after the outbreak at Ysgol Eifionydd, in Porthmadog. [North Wales]. Dr Richard Roberts, head of the vaccine preventable disease programme of public health Wales, added: "Measles is highly contagious, spreads very easily and can be extremely serious. "The outbreak in North Wales continues to make children very ill. "If this kind of outbreak can happen there, it can happen in any school in Wales.

"Although the uptake of MMR in Wales has improved greatly over the past 10 years, it is still the case that thousands of Welsh children enter school each year not fully vaccinated and at risk of catching measles, mumps or rubella. "Thousands will leave school in the same vulnerable condition. "MMR is a safe and effective vaccine, and is available free from your local surgery," he added.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap alerts
<promed@promemail.org>

[So far there have been no confirmed reports of measles cases within the South Wales area in 2012. - Mod.CP]


